        </head>
        <div2>
          <head>
            <title type="main">
              <hi rend="b">SANTA CRUZ CONFERENCE: BLAKE &amp; CRITICISM</hi>
            </title>
          </head>
          <p>The National Endowment for the Humanities has approved funding for the conference, which the
sponsors hope will bring into the open the collision between Blake studies and the concerns, values, and
strategies of contemporary critical theory. Ever more perceived as a key document at the origins of
post-modern consciousness, Blake’s work arguably anticipates and contests many contemporary and often
anti-humanistic critical formulations. The conference will focus on the profound role Blake’s work has to
play in any new organization and interpretation of humanistic studies. The conference will be held 21 and 22
May 1982 at the campus of the University of California, Santa Cruz. Detailed information concerning the
program will appear in the next issue of <hi rend="i">Blake</hi> and will also be available from The
Conference on Blake and Criticism, Literature Board, Kresge College, UCSC, Santa Cruz, CA 95064.</p>
        </div2>
